Having `self.event1`,`self.event2` etc as frozenset instead of set (see [here](https://github.com/pgmpy/pgmpy/blob/dev/pgmpy/independencies/Independencies.py#L189)) have advantage because they are hashable , moreover `__eq__` method that I have implemented can be simplified and will also lead to simplification of `__hash__` method for IndependenceAssertion and Independencies class.Since there is no notion for adding more assertion to a IndependenceAssertion, frozenset are better to use than sets because of above mentioned advantages.
Ping @ankurankan What are your views on it ?
@kshitij10496 Also since you are working with `__hash__` you might also want these changes.

This is pretty much like the the issue #316 and to get it working I did pretty much the same:

```
import numpy

def default(self, data):
        if isinstance(data, (date, datetime)):
            return data.isoformat()
        elif isinstance(data, Decimal):
            return float(data)
        elif isinstance(data, uuid.UUID):
            return str(data)
        elif isinstance(data, numpy.integer):
            return int(data)
        raise TypeError("Unable to serialize %r (type: %s)" % (data, type(data)))
```

I assume that also any other numpy type will be accepted, I haven't tested because the thing is that I'm not using any of these types explicitly but I was getting this while using the streaming_bulk:

```
elasticsearch.exceptions.SerializationError: ({'suggest_field': {'context': {'fieldname': 'stay_id', 'source': 'Source Test'}, 'input': ['99999'], 'payload': {'f
ield': 'stay_id', 'count': 1, 'value': '99999'}, 'weight': 1, 'output': '99999'}}, TypeError("Unable to serialize 1 (type: <class 'numpy.int64'>)",))
```
and you can see that the 99999 was passed as a string (I'm casting the value before sending it), but still I got the exception.

